Blockchain is a distributed ledger technology that allows for secure and decentralized record-keeping. It is essentially a database that is shared across a network of computers, and each computer maintains a copy of the database. This allows for a transparent and tamper-evident record of transactions and data.

The data in a blockchain is stored in blocks, which are linked together in a chronological sequence to form a chain. Each block contains a set of transactions or data, as well as a cryptographic hash of the previous block in the chain. This creates an immutable record of all transactions and data on the blockchain, as any tampering with a block would invalidate the hashes of all subsequent blocks in the chain.

Blockchain technology is often associated with cryptocurrencies like Bitcoin, as it was originally developed to enable secure and decentralized transactions without the need for a central authority or intermediary. However, blockchain has many other potential use cases beyond cryptocurrencies, such as supply chain management, identity verification, voting systems, and more.

There are several types of blockchain, including public, private, and consortium blockchains. Public blockchains are open to anyone and allow for anonymous participation, while private blockchains are restricted to a specific group of participants and may require permission to access. Consortium blockchains are a hybrid of public and private blockchains, where a group of organizations work together to maintain the blockchain.